<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yemeni Foreign Minister Departs for Amman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yemeni Foreign Minister Departs for Amman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1205054794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2150 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1205054794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 11 May (MENA)--Yemeni Foreign Minister 
Muhammad Salim Basindwah left Cairo this evening for Amman after 
a two-day visit to Cairo during which he met President Husni 
Mubarak. In a predeparture statement he said he conveyed to 
President Mubarak a verbal message from Yemeni President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih in which he explained the ongoing events in 
Yemen. He said that what is happening in Yemen is a 
confrontation of the remnants of renegades and secessionists, a 
confrontation with the participation of all the people, led by 
their armed forces, which are loyal to constitutional 
legitimacy. He noted that the new Yemeni defense minister who 
took the constitutional oath yesterday hails from the southern 
governorates as does the new naval forces commander. 
  Basindwah said he believed that the situation in Yemen has 
been decided and that what is going on will last no more than a 
day or two at most. He noted that during his meeting with 
President Mubarak he sensed considerable understanding, noting 
that the Yemeni people appreciate President Mubarak's great 
concern for Yemen's security and safety. He noted that he is 
going to Amman to convey a message to King Husayn of Jordan. 
His Jordan trip is part of a tour of Arab countries to convey 
verbal messages from President Salih to Arab leaders. 

</TEXT>

