<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Says Message From U.S. on `Opening Direct' Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Says Message From U.S. on `Opening Direct' Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1205111694 Paris AFP in English 0943 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1205111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 12 (AFP)--The United States recently 
sent a message to Iran on opening direct and formal 
negotiations, a newspaper said Thursday. 
  The written message contained assurances that the United 
States did not seek to undermine the Islamic republic and urged 
Iran "not to take seriously" anti-Tehran comments made by a US 
official during a recent Gulf tour, the daily SALAM said. 
  The assistant secretary of state for near eastern affairs, 
Robert Pelletreau, said earlier this week in the United Arab 
Emirates that Iran was a potential threat and he renewed US 
pledges to defend the region. 
  Tehran and Washington broke diplomatic ties in 1980 after 
Iranian radical students stormed US embassy here and took its 
staff hostage. 
  The United States has on several occasion called for direct 
negotiations to improve ties, but the two sides have yet to make 
a breakthrough. 
  The latest message also expressed concern over Russia's 
"future threats" against the region and said Iran was 
geographically "well-placed to counter such an influence," SALAM 
said. 
  But the paper said the message also criticised Iran's 
alleged 
human rights violations and support for international terrorism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
