<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th on Steps To Follow Gaza-Jericho Transition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th on Steps To Follow Gaza-Jericho Transition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1205162094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1430 GMT 12 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1205162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Nabil Sha'th, adviser to PLO </F>
Chairman Yasir 'Arafat, in Cairo, by Sa'id Mu'addi, in the 
studio, on 12 May; from the "With The Events" feature -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th in Cairo, good evening. 
Jericho tomorrow and Gaza next week. The challenges are great 
and you must have something to say on this occasion? 
  [Sha'th] The Palestinian people have been anticipating this 
day for a long time. True, there are challenges and 
difficulties and, true, there is responsibility that comes with 
freedom, but this is the opportunity for the Palestinian people 
to govern themselves on their soil. It starts here in Gaza and 
Jericho. This is the starting point for a people who have 
suffered for a long time. Now, the horizons of freedom and 
independence have begun to be seen over their soil. This people 
and their leadership must rise to the level of responsibility. 
Freedom and independence, even at the starting point, means 
great responsibility in terms of the people's security, freedom, 
free expression, participation in decisions, and the tiring work 
to achieve economic development and social justice. All these 
things are required from us when we take the first step in Gaza 
and Jericho. 
  [Mu'addi] The challenges are great, and the PLO is suffering 
a financial crisis that even caused a delay in the transfer of 
powers. What has happened? 
  [Sha'th] Yes, we are facing a financial problem. This 
problem has made our entry more difficult, but we are gradually 
overcoming this problem. I am confident that the presence of 
the police force inside Gaza and Jericho will be received with 
thousands of invitations and real support from the citizens. I 
believe we have all seen the cordial welcome they received. 
This, however, will not substitute for the money needed for 
equipment, uniforms, and transportation. We are seriously 
seeking to overcome these problems. The United States and the 
European Union have pledged funds, while equipment and other 
items will be coming from Japan, France, Greece, Germany, and 
other countries. We are working day and night to realize this 
support and transfer it to the Palestinian police force as soon 
as possible. 
  [Mu'addi] What will be the future steps after the assumption 
of powers and the establishment of self-rule in Gaza and 
Jericho, which will apparently start be next week? 
  [Sha'th] I have always told people the difficult phase is 
over, but the more difficult phase is still ahead of us. 
Undoubtedly, the transfer is important, but now we have to 
discuss how to form a competent, clean, and responsible 
government. How do we start the measures for economic 
development? How do we start preparations for elections? 
Above all, how do we continue negotiations to assume powers in 
the West Bank and reach an agreement on the interim phase in the 
West Bank and Gaza which will lead to the withdrawal of Israeli 
troops from cities and camps in the West Bank? All these 
matters are required. Some resulted from the signing of the 
agreement. Other topics must also be discussed after the 
transfer to Gaza and Jericho. These are missions for the 
forthcoming phase. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th has struggled for a long time to 
see the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli agreement. Will 
Nabil Sha'th be a member of the long-awaited Palestinian 
national authority? 
  [Sha'th] I will do whatever I am asked to do by my people 
and leadership. I devoted myself a long time ago to serve this 
people and their cause. I will not hesitate to serve my people 
in any position. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, thank you very much. 
  [Sha'th] Thank you, brother. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59382 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes093dd_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Results of Gaza-Jericho Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Results of Gaza-Jericho Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205192394 Algiers Voice of Palestine in Arabic 1702 GMT 
12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Voice of Palestine </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Assessing the results of the Gaza-Jericho agreement, 
Dr. Nabil Sha'th, head of the Palestinian delegation in the 
talks with Israel, has said that, in view of the Declaration of 
Principles signed in Oslo, we have obtained the best possible 
results. The worst of the Oslo agreement was the issues we 
decided to postpone -- for example, the settlements, the issue 
of the 1948 refugees, external security, and Jerusalem. 
  He added: In my opinion, we have obtained the best 
conditions even on the postponed issues, particularly the 
settlements. The whole conflict in this agreement was on how to 
reduce the area of the settlements and Israel's control over 
them during the transitional period. 
  Dr. Sha'th added that the agreement does not limit the 
demand 
for legitimate rights in the forthcoming period. We have added 
a clause to the effect that, whatever happens during the 
transitional period, our rights in the final phase will not be 
affected. The land in the West Bank and Gaza will also remain a 
single regional unit. There was also another clause which 
stipulated that whatever we signed in the Gaza-Jericho agreement 
did not constitute a renunciation of any of our rights. Sha'th 
also said that Israel has no right to reoccupy Gaza if 
settlements and settlers are exposed to danger. 
  Concerning foreign relations, Dr. Sha'th pointed out that 
Israel advocated that the Palestinian authority should not be 
allowed to exercise foreign relations. More than this, the PLO 
would not be allowed to exercise these relations on behalf of 
this authority, something which we rejected, he said. According 
to the agreement, countries and international organizations have 
the right to establish representation bureaus in the self-rule 
area, but the Palestinian authority cannot have embassies other 
than embassies of Palestine. 
  On the outstanding points of difference after the signing of 
the agreement, and the talks to be held about it, Dr. Sha'th 
said that all these issues are remnants of the Cairo security 
agreement: these are the Mawasi beach in Gaza, the Jericho 
crossing point, the Rafah crossing point, the area of Jericho, 
and the presence of Palestinian soldiers on the Allenby bridge. 
The talks will continue around four main axes, among which are 
the gaining of early authority in the West Bank, to include 
education, culture, tourism, taxes, social affairs, police, and 
so on. We will also start negotiating over the withdrawal of 
the Israeli forces from the West Bank and the holding of 
legislative elections in it. The four-man committee would start 
negotiating on the return of the refugees after a month. 
  Dr. Sha'th pointed out in a press statement that the talks 
on 
the refugees will revolve around two issues only. These are 
return measures and measures for maintaining security and order; 
there will not merely be discussions of the same principle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59383 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes093dd_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th on Authority, Prisoners, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th on Authority, Prisoners, Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1205194894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1850 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1205194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 12 May (MENA) -- Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's political adviser, has 
announced that President 'Arafat today approved the nomination 
of 15 members of the Palestinian Authority Council in Gaza and 
Jericho. He said that he informed Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin of this today so that the authorities would 
receive this information through official channels, and not to 
ask Israel for approval of the Council members. 
  He added that the Council chairman will be Yasir 'Arafat. It 
will include 14 members. These are: Zakariya al-Agha, Frayh 
Abu-Midyan, Faysal al-Husayni, Sa'ib 'Urayqat, Dr. Riyad 
al-Za'nun, Dr. Nabil Sha'th, Dr. 'Azmi al-Shu'aybi, Dr. 
'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Haj Ahmad, Ilyas Furayj, Ahmad Quray' alias 
Abu-'Ala', Samir Ghawshah, Yasir 'Amr, Mrs. Intisar al-Wazir 
alias Umm Jihad, and Mrs. Hanan al-'Ashrawi. 
  Sha'th told his news conference at the Foreign 
Correspondents 
Association in Cairo today that all these members have agreed to 
take part in the first Palestinian Authority Council, and their 
nomination has been approved by the PLO Executive Committee. 
  He noted that in the next four days, nine other members will 
be nominated, thus completing the formation of the Council, 
which will consist of 24 members. He said that the Council will 
start its duties immediately. He expected that this will take 
place on Wednesday, 18 May, in Gaza-Jericho and will constitute 
the first Palestinian National Authority on Palestinian 
territory. 
  Dr. Nabil Sha'th said that among the members of the Council 
are two former deportees, 'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Haj Ahmad and 'Azmi 
al-Shu'aybi. There are also two women: Dr. Hanan 'Ashrawi and 
Intisar al-Wazir. Among them also is one of Jerusalem's 
prominent sons, namely Faysal al-Husayni. 
  Dr. Sha'th added that the members of the Council have not 
yet 
been allocated their portfolios. He clarified that in 
accordance with the protocol that was signed last week, the PLO 
will continue to be the legitimate representative of the 
Palestinian people until their Palestinian state is established. 
He said that the Palestinian Authority in Gaza and Jericho is a 
part of the PLO, which supervises the liberated territories. 
  He added that foreign relations and the Palestine Liberation 
Army's affairs outside the Palestinian territories, as well as 
the national and international relations will continue to be the 
responsibilities of the PLO headquarters in Tunis. These 
affairs will be administered by three prominent members from the 
PLO Executive Committee--namely, Faruq Qaddumi for foreign 
diplomatic relations, Mahmud 'Abbas for national relations with 
Jewish organizations, and 'Abdallah Hurani for the Palestine 
Liberation Army. 
  On the delay in the Palestinian Authority's assumption of 
its 
duties in Gaza and Jericho, Sha'th said that this is due to very 
difficult circumstances because of the Palestinian diaspora. 
Thankfully, Saudi planes have transported members of the police 
from Yemen to Sinai. Saudi planes will also transport those 
coming from Algeria. Those coming from Libya will travel by car 
thousands of kilometers to cross through the al-Sallum border 
post to Sinai. 
  Egyptian planes have transported those coming from Sudan. 
  In this regard, Sha'th thanked President Husni Mubarak; King 
Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, the custodian of the Two Holy Mosques; 
and the Arab countries who have provided and continue to provide 
all the necessary facilities to transport these forces. 
  Sha'th expressed his belief that these forces will complete 
their arrival in Gaza and Jericho within the next few days. 
  He said that the Palestinian Authority would like the 
financial allocations from the donor countries to arrive quickly 
so that it can be spent on this police force. He noted that 
there is positive international action by the United States, 
Japan, and the European countries to hasten this process. Also, 
a batch of new cars for this police will arrive in Port Said 
sometime next week. 
  He said that this positive attitude reflects the extent of 
the world's interest in backing the implementation of the 
Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  On the relationships of the newborn Palestinian Authority 
in Gaza and Jericho, Dr. Sha'th said that this authority is part 
of the PLO, and although the latter is entrusted with 
representing the Palestinian people and negotiating and signing 
on its behalf, the Authority will be in charge of implementing 
the agreement on the scene. He added: Both the Palestinian 
people and Israel want to the retain the PLO at present. The 
Palestinians believe that the PLO is their representative until 
the state of Palestine is officially established. Israel would 
like to continue to negotiate and cooperate with the PLO in 
order to avoid the establishment of the Palestinian state. But, 
he added, the establishment of this state has become inevitable, 
no matter how long it takes. 
  In reply to a question about Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin's recent statement that Jerusalem is the capital of the 
State of Israel, Dr. Sha'th said: Rabin has no right to say 
this because, according to the Declaration of Principles, 
Jerusalem is an issue in the bilateral negotiations. If Rabin 
wishes it to be the capital of Israel, we in turn insist on 
making Jerusalem the capital of Palestine. He added: Since 
Israel has agreed to share the land of Palestine with us, why 
does it not agree then to let us both share Jerusalem? 
  In reply to a question on why Israel has not released the 
remaining Palestinian prisoners and detainees, Dr. Sha'th 
emphasized that he is confident that they will all be released. 
He explained that Israel would like to hand over many of them 
to the Palestinian Authority when it takes over, especially 
those convicted of ordinary crimes. Their cases will be left 
for the Palestinian Authority to decide on. As for the members 
of the Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] and al-Jihad 
movements, they have not been released so far because they have 
not signed a declaration to the Israeli authorities accepting 
the peace agreement. Maybe they do not want to sign such a 
declaration for the Israeli authorities but might sign for the 
Palestinian Authority so as to be released. 
  On 'Arafat's entry into Gaza and Jericho, Sha'th referred to 
'Arafat's statements that this will take place in early June. 
But, he added, 'Arafat has his own surprises. We don't know. 
The date might be before then. 
  On the differences between the Palestinian organizations, 
especially Hamas and al-Jihad, Dr. Sha'th said that there is an 
agreement that these differences should be kept within the 
democratic framework and not turned into acts of violence. He 
stressed his conviction that all the Palestinian organizations 
care about this democratic dialogue in order to establish the 
Palestinian state and ensure the success of the agreement as the 
first step toward the establishment of the state of Palestine. 
  Dr. Sha'th went on to say that the PLO, which is 
headquartered in Tunis, will remain in charge of the affairs of 
the refugees outside the liberated areas in the West Bank and 
the Gaza Strip and that the Palestine National Council [PNC], 
which includes members from inside and outside the territories, 
will remain the highest legislative Palestinian authority. 
  Sha'th went on to say that the coming elections in the West 
Bank and the Gaza Strip, which are scheduled to be held after 
three months, will be for the election of the members of the PNC 
from inside the territories, who were formerly appointed. He 
said: These members comprise a third of the PNC members but at 
the same time constitute the Palestinian Authority's parliament 
inside the territories. 
  In response to a question about the Palestinian diplomatic 
missions abroad, he said that they will remain the prerogative 
of the PLO headquartered in Tunis, but all countries will have 
the right to open representation offices in Gaza and Jericho 
until the Palestinian state is established. 
  On the new Palestinian ambassador in Cairo, Sha'th said that 
Acting Ambassador Zuhdi al-Qidrah will be appointed the 
Palestinian state's ambassador in Cairo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

