<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Mediation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Mediation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1205155494 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 12 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM1205155494 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Shaykh 'Abdallah al-Ahmar, speaker of the </F>
House of Representatives and leader of the Yemeni Reform 
Grouping, by Sulayman al-Nimr in Riyadh on 11 May] 
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] [Al-Nimr] Do you believe that 
the regime in Sanaa will continue the war, or will it accept 
mediation and dialogue with 'Ali Salim al-Bid? 
  [Al-Ahmar] It is illogical to hold a dialogue with the gang 
and the rebel leader. However, it is possible to hold a 
dialogue with the Socialist Party as a party and with the 
elements that are not bloodthirsty or rebellious, and with the 
elements that did not drag the country into this situation. In 
the end the Socialist Party is a political party, and we are 
committed to democracy and pluralism. [passage omitted] 
  [Al-Nimr] It has been reported that Yemeni Reform Grouping 
elements are fighting alongside northern forces against the 
Socialist Party's forces. 
  [Al-Ahmar] The war is still a military war. No civilians 
are taking part in it. The war is between the state and the 
rebels. 
  [Al-Nimr] Do you believe that tribes could intervene in 
favor of one party? 
  [Al-Ahmar] The tribes have not intervened so far, and we do 
not want them to intervene at all. [passage omitted] 
  [Al-Nimr] Do you agree to a cease-fire now? 
  [Al-Ahmar] We did not start the war. 
  [Al-Nimr] If mediation is offered to secure a cease-fire, 
will you accept it? 
  [Al-Ahmar] We will not turn down the mediation of any 
fraternal or friendly state, provided it is based on the fact 
that legitimacy cannot be harmed, democracy and unity cannot be 
harmed, and that the Army is the state's army, so it is 
impermissible for a section or a battalion of it to remain 
rebellious or loyal to any power other than the state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

