<DOCNO> FBIS4-59435 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes093_j_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-'Attas Says Dismissal Decision `Unconstitutional' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-'Attas Says Dismissal Decision `Unconstitutional' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1305060794 London MBC Television in Arabic 2100 GMT 12 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1305060794 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with Prime Minister Haydar Abu-Bakr </F>
al-'Attas with London MBC TV correspondent 'Aziz Fahmi, in 
Florida; date not given--recorded] 
  [Text] Prime Minister Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas has 
described the decision to dismiss him as unconstitutional. He 
said in an interview with an MBC correspondent in Florida, 'Aziz 
Fahmi, that the United States is continuing its contacts with 
him. He said the war constitutes a real danger for Yemeni unity. 
  [Al-'Attas] The declaration of war was clearly an act 
harming 
unity and breaking every bond between the sons of the Yemeni 
people. We did not expect our brothers in Sanaa to resort to 
such methods. This is why, as I have already said, they have 
portrayed the situation as an annexation of the south to the 
north. Their behavior shows that they are secessionists. With 
regard to the war, which totally contradicts unity, there can be 
no unity with war. Whatever the situation and whichever side's 
forces occupy the land of the other party, it cannot be seen as 
a victory. 
  [Fahmi] What is the constitutional stance on the 
presidential 
measures to dismiss you and all the southern officials? 
  [Al-'Attas] Undoubtedly, the measures are not 
constitutional. 
It is the right of the House of Representatives under normal 
circumstances to withdraw confidence from the government or from 
any minister. But the Presidential Council has no right to 
dismiss a minister or the prime minister. So this decision is 
not constitutional, even under normal circumstances, never mind 
in the circumstances in Yemen now, which are not normal. 
  [Fahmi] What is the U.S. Administration's stance on events 
in 
Yemen and has it accepted your dismissal as prime minister? 
  [Al-'Attas] We maintain dealings with the U.S. 
Administration 
and are still in contact with the U.S. State Department. In my 
meetings with State Department officials, since the start of the 
crisis they have expressed their dissatisfaction with the 
military course of the political crisis in the country. [end 
recording] 
  Later tonight, a U.S. State Department spokesman clarified 
to 
MBC that his country has adopted no stance on the position of 
al-'Attas, dismissed by Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 
The U.S. official, who asked to remain anonymous, said that 
Washington is focusing on stopping the acts of aggression 
between the Yemenis and on finding ways for negotiations to be 
held between the north and the south to reach a peaceful 
solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

