Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   GPC's Al-Iryani on Arab `Interference,' Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GPC's Al-Iryani on Arab `Interference,' Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1305083694 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 12 May 94 
pp1,4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1305083694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on interview with Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, </F>
Yemeni planning and development minister and member of the 
General Committee of the General People's Congress, by Hasin 
al-Bunyan in Riyadh; date not given] 
  [Text] Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, Yemeni planning and 
development minister and member of the General Committee 
(Political Bureau) of the General People's Congress [GPC], has 
declared that "Sanaa will continue the war until the mutiny 
against legitimacy led by 'Ali Salim al-Bid is defeated." 
  He said: "We will continue the war even for 100 years 
because 
we see nothing wrong with fighting in defense of constitutional 
legitimacy, until the mutiny falls." 
  He added: "We know that war is not easy and that the way to 
Aden to put down the mutiny will not be easy but whoever imposed 
that war must pay the price." He emphasized that "the only 
condition for stopping the war is to recognize the legitimate 
constitutional leadership and place all the armed forces under 
the command of President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, the supreme 
commander of the armed forces." 
  He said that Sanaa absolutely refuses to receive Arab forces 
to disengage the warring forces in Yemen. "We cannot possibly 
allow such interference because we are fighting an internal 
mutiny, fighting to end and put down that mutiny. Do the Arabs 
accept fragmentation of a homeland? Would any Arab country 
accept interference to end a mutiny in it?" 
  He added: "We welcome Arab mediation if it is within the 
context of fulfilling constititonal legitimacy and the context 
of dealing with the state of unity." He also said that 'Ali 
Salim al-Bid's rejection of the legitimate decisions dismissing 
him, al-'Attas, and some ministers is not important because he 
is, after all, a mutineer. He emphasized that the legitimate 
forces will continue the war and the fighting "because we are 
fighting for a cause. A mutineer has no cause. That is the 
difference." 
  Dr. al-Iryani stressed that the northern forces "have not 
retreated one inch on the Abyan front," and that "fighting is 
now raging in al-'Anad base, the last stronghold of the rebel 
forces." He said that the southern forces are now concentrated 
in the area of al-'Alam, north of Aden, considered to be the 
city's first and last line of defense. He confirmed "the 
surrender to the legitimate forces of 550 officers and soldiers 
from al-Labwazah Brigade on the Kirsh front with all their arms 
equipment." Dr. al-Iryani also confirmed "the surrender of the 
southern 30th Brigade three days ago. That brigade no longer 
exists in the Abyan Governorate and al-'Urqub area." He added 
that he contacted Sanaa yesterday and was assured that 
"al-'Amaliqah Brigade has not retreated from its positions in 
Zinjibar and Mudiyah and that it is there in full strength." He 
emphasized that "not a single gun, tank, or piece of arms was 
lost on the Abyan front. These forces are now advancing towards 
al-'Alam area." 
  On the conflicting reports on how close the northern forces 
are to Aden, al-Iryan affirmed that these reports did not come 
from military sources, but he said that forces from Khalid Camp, 
al-Wahdah Brigade, and the 125th Brigade are occupying the area 
of Kharaz west of Aden. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

