<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oil Minister Sees Arab Intervention as `Acceptable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Oil Minister Sees Arab Intervention as `Acceptable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1205152294 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 12 May 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PM1205152294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Oil Minister Salih Abu-Bakr Bin-Husaynun by </F>
Shafiq al-Asadi in Abu Dhabi on 11 May] 
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] [Al-Asadi] The northerners 
say they have captured al-'Anad base and reached the approaches 
to Aden. 
  [Bin-Husaynun] Al-'Anad has not been captured, nor have 
northern forces reached Dar Sa'd, as 'Abd-al-'Aziz 
'Abd-al-Ghani, member of the Yemeni Presidential Council, and 
Planning Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani said. Maybe they 
do not know what is happening on the battlefield. It can be 
said that their claim is absolutely baseless. They must know 
that it is very difficult to reach Aden, perhaps not in their 
time, nor will it be by force. [passage omitted] 
  [Al-Asadi] What is your opinion of the decision to dismiss 
you from the cabinet? 
  [Bin-Husaynun] I do not recognize a decision of that kind, 
because those who made it do not enjoy legitimacy. The 
legitimacy collapsed on 27 April after the declaration of war on 
the Yemeni people. Anyone who declares war on his own people 
does not deserve or have any legitimacy. 
  [Al-Asadi] Do you believe there has been Arab interference 
in current events in Yemen? 
  [Bin-Husaynun] I believe that some elements from some Arab 
states are participating alongside northern forces in the 
fighting. It has been stated that there are some Iraqis and 
Sudanese elements on the battlefield. 
  [Al-Asadi] Aden reports said today (Wednesday) that northern 
aircraft are using Sudanese airports to bombard targets in the 
south.... 
  [Bin-Husaynun] The relationship between Khartoum and Sanaa 
and between President 'Umar al-Bashir and 'Abd 'Abdallah Salih 
shows Sudan's support for the northern forces which have 
declared war on the Yemeni people. We regret these matters and 
hope that Arab brothers will not become a party to this 
conflict. If they cannot contribute to resolving the crisis and 
securing a cease-fire, they should stay neutral. 
  [Al-Asadi] What is your interpretation of the north's offer 
of an immediate cease-fire, provided Aden accepts the legitimacy? 
  [Bin-Husaynun] That is up to them. Sometimes they accept 
and other times they do not. But conditions are not conducive 
to a cease-fire. Some say that a cease-fire should be announced 
first, and then a dialogue at the negotiating table should 
begin. For our part, we have decided to accept a cease-fire and 
responded to the appeal made by some brothers. This is because 
of the Socialist Party leadership's keenness to spare Yemeni 
blood, not as a result of weakness. 
  [Al-Asadi] So do you accept the intervention of Arab forces 
to disengage the warring forces? 
  [Bin-Husaynun] Any initiative or effort to stop the 
fighting, return to dialogue, and implement the Pledge and 
Accord Document is acceptable. 
  [Al-Asadi] Including the dispatch of Arab forces to Yemen? 
  [Bin-Husaynun] We are talking about any effort, including 
the intervention of Arab forces. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

