<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Philippine Workers `Only Ones Left;' Fear for Safety </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Philippine Workers `Only Ones Left;' Fear for Safety </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1205111194 Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1205111194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City GMA-7 Radio-Television Arts Network 
in Tagalog 0930 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Tagalog </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Philippine overseas contract workers [OCW's] 
trapped in Yemen have been waiting for five days to be 
repatriated to the Philippines. In an interview with GMA Radio, 
a Philippine OCW identified as Josie Oliva said they have been 
advised to return home immediately. According to Oliva, she and 
30 other OCW's are safe and are staying at the Sheraton Hotel. 
She fears that if they are unable to leave today, their lives 
may be in danger. 
  In this connection, the Department of Foreign Affairs has 
revealed that two C-130 planes from the Philippine Air Force are 
set to fly to Yemen to retrieve the Phlippine OCW's once a 
landing permit is secured. 
  [Begin Oliva recording, in progress] ...as of now we are 
safe; we have not yet been affected in any way. But we do not 
know about tomorrow; we do not know what will happen tomorrow. 
They have already advised us to get out because we are the only 
ones left here. As I mentioned before, all other nationals have 
been rescued by their respective governments. Only the 
Philippine Government has not acted. We are still okay, 
including my brother and my uncle, but we do not have any 
outside contact. We cannot communicate because there is no 
international line available here. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

