<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Refusal To Address Bugging Charges Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Refusal To Address Bugging Charges Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205145294 Tehran IRNA in English 1431 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London, May 12, IRNA -- The British Government 
refused to comment Thursday on its MI6 intelligence service 
bugging the Iranian Embassy in London. 
  A spokesman for the Foreign Office was adamant that there 
was 
no official response to hidden microphones being found in the 
newly renovated mission, which only reopened six months ago. He 
did not expect any comment would be made about the illegal 
bugging. 
  The tight-lipped reaction was met with a news blackout in 
the 
British media, which even extended to the PRESS ASSOCIATION, the 
UK's national news agency, not carrying the Wednesday night 
report of the disclosure by Iran's president, Hashemi-Rafsanjani. 
  With dailies exercising the same trend and only a few 
carrying extracts from foreign agencies, the suggestion was that 
there had been a blanket ban imposed to hide the government's 
humiliation of being caught red-handed contravening 
international law. 
  The disclosure also reveals that the UK's recent propaganda 
campaign to discredit Iran was orchestrated to cover the 
embarrassment of being found spying on a foreign embassy in 
London. 
  The Iranian Foreign Ministry disclosed that the devices were 
discovered before the UK Government, assisted by the British 
press, launched smears two weeks ago that claimed Iranian 
intelligence had links with the IRA. 
  Bugging a foreign mission is nothing new to British 
intelligence. Former agent, Peter Wright, has revealed in his 
"Spycatcher" book that such clandestine activities extended to 
even embassies of Britain's allies. 
  It has also been disclosed that the UK has tapped the telex 
lines of IRNA in London, when the interception warrant was found 
to be still in place long after the location of its bureau was 
removed from Leicester Square in 1987. 
  All international telecommunications are commonly assumed to 
be monitored by the government's communications headquarters 
(GCHQ) in Cheltenham, western England. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59463 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes093_l_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF Completes Evacuation of Rafah Installations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IDF Completes Evacuation of Rafah Installations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1205142894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1400 GMT 12 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1205142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The IDF [Israel Defense Forces] has evacuated all 
its installations in the city of Rafah in the Gaza Strip, but 
the transfer of powers in the place has still not taken place. 
This is reported by our military affairs correspondent Karmela 
Menashe. 
  Commander Yitzhaq Aharonovich, chief of the Border Police, 
visited the Gaza Strip today to supervise the evacuation of his 
forces from the area. Aharonovich said the Border Police is 
currently preparing to undertake the task of ensuring the safe 
passage of Israelis in the autonomy areas. It is also preparing 
for the joint patrols with the Palestinians, slated to start in 
the next few days. 

</TEXT>

