<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jericho Turned Over to Palestinian Control </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jericho Turned Over to Palestinian Control </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1305115894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1100 GMT 13 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1305115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The town of Jericho and its environs were turned 
over to Palestinian control approximately 30 minutes ago. Major 
General Ilan Biran, the commander of the Central Command, shook 
the head of General Hajj 'Isma'il, the commander of the 
Palestinian al-Aqsa Brigade, wished him success in his mission, 
and offered the IDF's [Israel Defense Forces] cooperation. Maj. 
Gen. Biran said that the IDF troops had implemented the 
withdrawal with full success. 
  Our correspondent Moti Amir reports that 462 Palestinian 
policemen have entered Jericho with approximately another 1,000 
expected to arrive later. Local residents enthusiastically 
welcomed the Palestinian policemen and flew PLO flags from their 
cars. 
  Maj. Gen. Biran signed an order banning Israeli citizens 
from 
entering the Palestinian autonomous areas over the coming days. 
The decree went into effect as soon as the Palestinian police 
assumed responsibility for the area. An IDF spokesman asserted 
that the major general signed the order due to security 
considerations. The entrance of Israelis into the Jericho area 
will only be permitted after security conditions there make this 
possible. 
  Yesterday, Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Chief of Staff 
Ehud Baraq held up the entry of Palestinian policemen from 
Jordan and Rafah for many hours after the PLO failed to meet the 
conditions of the agreement and did not transfer a list with the 
names of the members of the Palestinian authority to Israel. 
  Our political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports that this was 
a condition stipulated by the agreement signed by the PLO and 
Israel and Yasir 'Arafat promised to send the list by last 
Wednesday [11 May]. However, Israel was only given a partial 
list of 15 names out of the 24 members of the Palestinian 
authority late last night. Only then were the policemen 
permitted to cross the border checkpoints. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59505 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes094_l_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF Commander on Jericho Turnover </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IDF Commander on Jericho Turnover </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1305104294 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1015 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1305104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Golan Yokhpaz from Jericho -- live] </F>
  [Text] [Yokhpaz] The historic handshake between Major 
General Ilan Biran, the commander of the Central Command, and 
the Palestinian commander took place several moments ago. Major 
General Biran, you are speaking live on IDF Radio. What were 
your feelings at that moment? 
  [Biran] It was a very exciting moment. We have achieved a 
joint success. I hope this success is only the beginning and we 
will see over the next few days whether things are fully working 
out. There is a great deal of promise but reality is a bit more 
difficult and we must be realistic. 
  [Yokhpaz] What did the Palestinian officer say to you? 
  [Biran] We have been discussing things for many days and 
these issues are not for comment over the radio. 
  [Yokhpaz] Did you give them any last-minute tips prior to 
their entrance? 
  [Biran] Yes, we have agreed on our respective duties. 
  [Yokhpaz] Major General Biran, could you bid a short 
farewell live on IDF Radio to the Jericho autonomous area? 
  [Biran] We have implemented the government's decision. I 
salute the soldiers here who did an excellent job. 
  [Yokhpaz] That was Maj. Gen. Ilan Biran at the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] checkpoint at the entrance to what is now the 
Palestinian autonomous area in Jericho. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

