<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Musaymir Recapture </H4>

<F P=102> NC1405071994 Paris AFP in English 2353 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1405071994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sanaa, May 14 (AFP) -- Southern troops suffered 
"heavy losses" when northern forces recaptured the town of 
Musaymir, northwest of Aden, a spokesman for the Defense 
Ministry announced overnight Friday. 
  The report came as northern leaders rejected as "nothing 
new" 
a seven-point ceasefire plan put forward by their southern 
counterparts. 
  Northern troops advanced in the town of al-Dali', 90 
kilometers (55 miles) north of Aden, which controls one of the 
main routes to the former southern capital, SABA' news agency 
quoted him as saying. 
  Reports on the developments at al-Dali' were contradictory 
Friday, with each camp claiming control of the area. 
  The spokesman said southern forces also suffered heavy 
losses 
at Abyan where large amounts of weapons and ammunition, 
including 18 tanks and four armored vehicles, were seized. 
[passage omitted] 
  Arab League delegates carrying a message from the 
organization's Secretary General 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid calling 
for an immediate halt to the civil war were due to meet with 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih on Saturday. 
  Friday's peace plan, proposed by the southern Yemen 
Socialist 
Party (YSP), called for an immediate end to the nine-day war and 
the creation of a national unity government. 
  But northern leaders repeated demands made at the beginning 
of the conflict for southern leaders to surrender. 

</TEXT>

