Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sanaa Forces Advance Toward Aden </H4>

<F P=102> JN1605085394 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0720 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1605085394 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 16 May (INA) -- Yemeni Army units yesterday 
advanced 30 km into Haraz region, around 65 km west of Aden, 
which they had captured last Thursday [12 May]. 
  The commander of the Khalid Bin-al-Walid Camp, operating 
with 
the Yemeni Command, told an INA correspondent in Sanaa -- who 
was with a press mission on a visit to the region organized by 
the Yemeni Information Ministry -- that the Khalid Bin-al-Walid 
and 'Urubah Brigades had inflicted huge losses on the 
secessionist troops, forcing them to retreat and surrender. 
  The commander said the 25th Mechanized Brigade, one of the 
strongest units of the secessionists, 50 km west of Aden, was 
among the secessionist troops that surrendered to the forces of 
legitimacy in the battles that erupted on 12 May. 
  Several Yemeni military commanders have asserted that a 
large 
number of citizens were supporting the forces of legitimacy 
against the remnants of the secessionists. 
  The Yemeni government's forces of legitimacy are advancing 
toward Aden, the secessionists' key stronghold, from the 
following axes: the Abyan-al-'Anad axis, from Abyan, al-Hawtah, 
and al-'Alam, 12-15 km east of Aden; from the northern axis, 
around 80 km from the al- 'Anad Base, which is around 60 km 
north of Aden; and from the west in the direction of the Aden 
garrison (Salah-al-Din Camp), which is around 15-50 km north and 
west of Aden in the direction of Bab el Mandeb. 
  Military sources say the fall of the al-'Anad Base will 
signal the collapse of the secessionists' main point of strength. 
  The forces of legitimacy are currently in control of regions 
4 km away from the al-'Anad Base, which is expected to fall 
within the next 24 hours, according to official Yemeni military 
sources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

