<H3> <TI>   Reaction Continues to Alleged Embassy Bugging </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction Continues to Alleged Embassy Bugging </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Daily: UK Violated Vienna Accord </H4>

<F P=102> LD1405095594 Tehran IRNA in English 0918 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1405095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 14, IRNA -- A morning English daily here 
Saturday [14 May] commented on the installation of bugging 
devices in the Iranian Embassy in London saying that the British 
Government faces the two charges of espionage and violation of 
the terms of the 1961 Vienna Convention regarding the concept of 
national sovereignty. 
  The Iranian Government's disclosure about this illegal act 
was "coincident with the ballyhoo started by the British 
Government on the alleged Iranian financial assistance for the 
Irish Republican Army (IRA)," noted the paper. 
  It argued that the Irish Americans were the greatest 
supporters of the IRA and their financial and logistic 
assistance to IRA, with the green light from the C.I.A., was 
considered normal and acceptable in international political 
circles. 
  While the statesmen in London found it prudent to condone 
any 
differences they might have with the U.S. over the issue of IRA, 
they apparently felt it was necessary to transfer their internal 
crisis to other parts of the world, said the paper. 
  Urging Iran's Government to continue to exert pressure until 
British authorities were ready to accept responsibilty, the 
paper concluded "we should not allow such glaring cases of 
violation of the country's national sovereignty be easily 
forgotten." 

</TEXT>

