Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Battles Rage for al-Dali', Kharaz </H4>

<F P=102> NC1305123794 Paris AFP in English 1117 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1305123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Sanaa, May 13 (AFP)--Rival Yemeni troops battled 
Friday for control of a key town north of Aden, as an Arab 
League team issued an urgent appeal for a ceasefire in the 
week-old civil war. 
  Northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and 
southern forces backing Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid were 
locked in a grim struggle for al-Dali', which lies near the 
former border between the old North and South Yemen. 
  The Sanaa authorities announced Thursday said the town had 
fallen, and a military spokesman said here Friday that "pockets 
of resistance" were being mopped up. 
  Northern reinforcements had been dispatched to al-Dali', 
which lies 90 kilometres (50 miles) north of Aden on a key road 
to a southern air base. 
  But military sources in Aden said southern troops had 
launched a counter-offensive and recaptured some positions 
around al-Dali'. 
  There was also another battle underway in the Kharaz region, 
120 kilometres (75 miles) west of Aden. 
  The defence ministry in Sanaa said northern forces were 
advancing and had inflicted heavy losses on a rival armoured 
brigade. 
  But as the rival communiques continued to fly, southern 
commander Colonel 'Ali Qasim Talib said that the northern 
offensive through Kharaz had been beaten back and the region was 
controlled by al- Bid's men. 
  And as the fighting raged on, an Arab League mission was due 
to hold urgent talks with Salih. 
  Muhammad Bayraqdar, the league's military affairs chief, 
urged Yemen's leaders to "immediately halt" the fighting and 
open a dialogue, which they have so far refused to do. 
  He was to give the president a message to that effect from 
the League secretary-general, Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid. 
  Salih and his northern leadership decided to oust al-Bid as 
vice president last week and sacked several southern ministers, 
branding them "secessionists" who should be put on trial. 
  Al-Bid's side in the meantime has demanded the withdrawal of 
northern forces from the south. 
  Saudi Arabia's King Fahd has spoken by telephone with both 
Salih and al-Bid, and Gulf states have issued appeals for an end 
to the fighting, which has shattered the fragile unity of Yemen, 
an impoverished country on the southern tip of the Arabian 
peninsula. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59606 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes094_j_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-094 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of 13-16 May Clashes in North, South </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sanaa Denies Loss of Aircraft, Ship </H4>

<F P=102> JN1305162494 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1525 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1305162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 13 May (INA) -- The Yemeni Defense Ministry 
has dismissed the reported downing of three warplanes of its Air 
Force close to Bab el Mandeb at the Red Sea and the sinking of a 
warship off the port city of Aden. 
  Citing a military source at the Defense Ministry and the 
Staff Command today, the Yemeni News Agency, SABA', denied there 
were any boats in the vicinity, labelling the report mere 
fabrication. 
  The dismissed Yemeni Navy chief, Colonel 'Ali Qasim Talib, 
yesterday, Thursday, announced the separatist forces Wednesday 
shot down three warplanes close to Bab el Mandeb and sank a 
warship. 
  The Defense Ministry said the regular forces are continuing 
their advance in the Kharaz region, 120 km west of Aden city, 
having routed the 25th Mechanized Brigade at Kharaz Camp and 
seized all its weapons and equipment. 

</TEXT>

