<DATE1>  15 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak Statement on Yemen, Gaza-Jericho </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak Statement on Yemen, Gaza-Jericho </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1605061494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2130 GMT 15 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1605061494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 15 May (MENA)--President Husni Mubarak has 
renewed his call to Yemeni leaders to stop the fighting and 
resort to dialogue, stressing that war solves nothing. 
  In a statement to be published in the 16 May issue of the 
newspaper MAYU, President Mubarak said: Stop the fighting. War 
terminates unity; it does not preserve it. The Yemeni people 
are paying the price with their own blood and their vital 
installations, which are being destroyed. War will solve no 
problem anywhere, even if one side triumphs over another. The 
basis is always dialogue. 
  He added: We have always advised them not to resort to 
military force. We said unity must be achieved with the consent 
of the people. 
  Regarding the Gaza-Jericho Agreement, President Mubarak 
said: 
The Palestinian people are happy with this agreement. We are 
also happy to see that our Palestinian brothers have begun to 
restore their land and return to it in accordance with this 
agreement, which was the result of long and exhausting talks. 
  Referring to the crisis that occurred during the signing 
ceremony for the agreement in Cairo on 4 May, Mubarak said: 
What happened on the day of the signing of the agreement in 
Cairo--the dispute over the maps, their not being signed, and 
then our return to the stage after bridging the gaps--is the 
most eloquent proof of the efforts we all exerted and the 
strenuous talks that ended with the signing of the agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

