<DATE1>  14 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa Comments on London Talks, Self-Rule, Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa Comments on London Talks, Self-Rule, Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1405070594 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0510 GMT 14 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1405070594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa, in London, by </F>
reporter Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz, in Cairo; date not given; from 
the "Dialogue from Afar" program -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa, 
can you tell us something about the nature of the talks you have 
had with British officials during your current visit to London? 
  [Musa] The talks dealt with many issues. These included 
bilateral issues, regional issues pertaining to the Middle East 
and Africa, and international political and economic issues. 
Therefore, the talks with the prime minister, the foreign 
secretary, other ministers, and members of the House of Commons 
Foreign Affairs Committee were exhaustive and detailed. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What was your impression regarding British 
attitude to these issues, considering that these important 
issues are of interest not only to Egypt but to the entire 
Middle East area? 
  [Musa] I detected British interest in these issues. We are 
interested in talking to all influential states about a number 
of problems, including, for example, Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
peace process in the Middle East, and the situations in the 
Gulf, South Africa, and Somalia. All these issues are of 
interest to a large number of states, the important states. 
This is what prompts us to act on the international level. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What is the significance of your current 
visit to London at this particular time? 
  [Musa] The purpose of the visit is to hold consultations, 
particularly during the important period preceding the 
resumption of the peace process on the other tracks. The 
purpose is also to consult on the implementation of the 
Palestinian-Israeli agreement, the new era that has begun in 
South Africa, the critical situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina in 
which Britain is playing a big role, and a number of other 
existing problems. [passage omitted] 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Minister Musa, regarding the situation in 
Yemen, everyone is asking which way the Yemeni crisis is 
heading? What do you say? 
  [Musa] I tell you that the Yemeni crisis is extremely bad. 
Fighting and bloodshed cannot augur good or lead to a settlement 
or unity. At any rate, we have been following the situation. 
As you may know, President Husni Mubarak has received envoys 
from both parties to the conflict in Yemen. Egypt is playing an 
extremely active role to contain this crisis. We undertook this 
role even before the outbreak of the fighting. The outbreak of 
fighting introduced new elements into the issue. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Can we expect a solution to the Yemeni 
crisis soon, or will it worsen? 
  [Musa] We hope that matters will not reach that point, 
although there is fear now that matters might get out of hand 
unless the fighting stops. I do not think--and we in Egypt do 
not think--that there will be victor or vanquished in this 
conflict. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Minister Musa, what is your opinion of the 
start of Palestinian self-rule in Gaza and Jericho? 
  [Musa] We hope it will succeed. This is a particularly 
difficult time, and the future of the Palestinian-Israeli 
relations, the settlement of the Palestinian issue, and progress 
on the other tracks depend on it. Therefore, we wish our 
Palestinian brothers success in this endeavor. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa, thank you very 
much and we welcome you as always on the airwaves of the Voice 
of the Arabs Radio. 
  [Musa] Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

