Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Musa on Yemen, Sudan, Peace Process, Lockerbie </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa on Yemen, Sudan, Peace Process, Lockerbie </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1405093294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0710 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1405093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 14 May (MENA) -- Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
has called for an immediate cease-fire between the rival Yemeni 
parties and for the start of a dialogue with help from the Arabs. 
  In an interview with AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT newspaper today, Musa 
said talks should be the basis of the process to salvage Yemeni 
unity and that any military clash will be futile because there 
will be no victor, only bloodshed and continuous conflict. 
  He emphasized that the military conflict strikes at the core 
of Yemeni unity because unity should be based on mutual desire 
and the converging views of everyone--people and leaders. 
  On reports of foreign interventions in the Yemeni war, Musa 
said there is no information in this regard but there is talk 
that there are groups of returnees from Afghanistan who are 
pursuing certain goals in some areas of Yemen, but this issue is 
under strict observation by many countries. 
  Commenting on Egyptian-Sudanese relations, Musa said he 
intends to visit Sudan soon and noted that he had met with 
Sudanese President 'Umar al-Bashir and Foreign Minister Husayn 
Sulayman Abu-Salih during the inauguration of Nelson Mandela as 
president of South Africa. 
  In his interview, Musa discussed Egypt's role in the peace 
process, especially on the Syrian-Israeli track. He said Egypt 
does not impose its role, but such a role does exist. He added: 
Naturally, it is not our policy to intervene in certain tracks, 
but the Egyptian role is there and ready to serve the Arab 
brothers, including Syria. 
  Musa said: Egypt does not play the role of mediator in these 
negotiations, because we are an Arab state committed to Arab 
goals-- that is, a comprehensive withdrawal, the Palestinian 
people's right to self-determination, and a comprehensive and 
just peace between the Arabs and Israel. 
  Answering a question on the Lockerbie issue and whether he 
had discussed it in his talks with British officials, he said: 
We explained our stand on this issue to the British officials, 
considering the continuous, intensive contacts between President 
Mubarak and Colonel al-Qadhdhafi. Our clear stand is that we 
are against any further escalation of this issue. 
  On the idea of a Middle Eastern market and asked if there is 
a strategic Egyptian study of the issue, he said: Of course 
Egypt is conducting concentrated studies concerning the region's 
economic future in peacetime. However, Musa added, there is no 
proposal for a Middle Eastern market; the whole issue is no more 
than an idea that has often been floated. He said that there is 
no study about a Middle Eastern market and it will not 
materialize unless peace is established. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

